+    content: `# Charging Port Repair vs Replacement in Johannesburg: What You Actually Need to Know
+
+Your iPhone won't charge. You plug in the cable, nothing happens. Panic sets in, is it the cable, the battery, or the charging port itself? In our Hyde Park workshop, we see this problem at least twice a week, and the decision between repairing and replacing isn't always straightforward. The good news: most charging port failures can be fixed without replacing your entire device, and it's significantly cheaper than Apple's quote or buying new.
+
+Let's walk through what actually happens when a charging port fails, what your real options are, and how much you're likely to spend in Johannesburg.
+
+## What Actually Fails Inside a Charging Port
+
+Charging ports aren't simple holes in your phone. They're precision connectors with dozens of tiny metal pins or contacts that carry power and data signals. Over time, three things go wrong most often: corrosion from humidity (Johannesburg's winter dryness is actually better than coastal regions, but summer moisture still penetrates), physical damage from worn-out cables or rough insertion, and accumulated lint or dust blocking the connection.
+
+We've assessed more than 25,000 devices across Johannesburg and surrounding areas, and roughly 70% of "dead" charging ports are actually repairable. The port itself isn't broken, the pins are bent, corroded, or dirty. This matters because a bend can be straightened. Corrosion can be cleaned. Dirt can be removed. None of these require a full port replacement.
+
+The remaining 30% have genuine hardware failure: cracked solder joints where the port connects to the logic board, or a port that's physically shattered beyond reconnection. That's when replacement becomes necessary.
+
+## Repair: The Faster, Cheaper Route
+
+Port repair in our Hyde Park workshop takes between 2-4 hours for most phones, sometimes less if it's purely a cleaning job. We start with our R599 diagnostic assessment, which tells us exactly what's wrong. That R599 covers the inspection, testing with our equipment, and a detailed explanation of what we found.
+
+If it's corrosion, we use specialist cleaning solutions and microscopic brushes to restore the pins without damaging the delicate connectors. If pins are bent, our technicians carefully straighten them using precision tools. Once repaired, we run a full charge cycle and data sync test before you leave.
+
+Cost-wise, a straightforward repair runs a fraction of Apple's quote or any brand-new device. And because we stand by our work, repairs come with up to a 3-year warranty, meaning if that same port fails again due to our repair, we fix it free.
+
+This is the route we recommend for anyone whose device is otherwise healthy. Your phone works fine; it just needs to charge properly again.
+
+## Replacement: When Repair Isn't Possible
+
+If the port is physically destroyed or the solder joints on your logic board have fractured, repair isn't viable. The entire port assembly must come out and a new one soldered in. This is technically more complex and takes 4-6 hours.
+
+Replacement is also the sensible choice if you've had the same port repaired before and it's failed again, sometimes the underlying board damage is too severe for repeated repairs to stick.
+
+Cost-wise, a full port replacement is still significantly cheaper than Apple's repair or a new device, though it's more expensive than a repair. However, it's a genuine permanent fix if done correctly, and it carries the same warranty.
+
+## Turnaround Times and Load Shedding Reality
+
+Here's something Apple stores won't tell you: load shedding affects our workshop. During Stage 6 cuts, we operate on limited power and extend turnaround time by a day. We manage this by scheduling major work around known load shedding windows and keeping backup power for critical diagnostics.
+
+For a standard repair with our R599 assessment included, expect 2-3 working days in normal conditions. Replacements take 4-5 working days because solder work must cool properly and be tested thoroughly.
+
+If your device is also showing signs of [liquid damage](/liquid-damage), turnaround extends another 1-2 days, we won't rush a repair if moisture is present. That's when our specialists assess whether the port is the only problem or if the [logic board](/logic-board-repair) has been compromised too.
+
+## Why Not Just Replace Your Device?
+
+We get this question often. A new iPhone in South Africa costs between R12,000 and R25,000+, depending on model. A new MacBook Pro sits at R35,000-R50,000. A charging port repair or replacement costs a fraction of that, and your device is back in your hands in days, not weeks waiting for stock.
+
+Most people don't realise: a phone with a broken charging port is otherwise perfectly functional. Your screen works. Your camera works. Your apps work. You just can't charge it. That's a genuine repair problem, not a replacement problem.
+
+## Our Process: What to Expect at ZA Support
+
+When you bring your device to our Hyde Park workshop, here's what happens. First, the R599 diagnostic: we test the charging circuit, the power management board, and the port itself. We'll know within an hour whether repair or replacement is necessary, and we'll give you a transparent quote with no hidden costs.
+
+If you authorise repair, your device goes into our workshop queue. You can [contact us to check status](/contact), and we message updates to your WhatsApp. Once complete, we run a full charge cycle, at least two hours of charging and discharging, to confirm stability before you collect.
+
+All repairs carry a 3-year hardware warranty and 30-day satisfaction guarantee. If the port fails again within warranty, we repair it free.
+
+## Cost Comparison: Rough Guide for Johannesburg
+
+A charging port assessment costs R599. A repair typically confirms after we assess your device. A replacement also confirms after diagnosis, the exact cost depends on your device model and whether the surrounding board needs rework. Apple's quote for the same work usually sits at R2,500-R4,500, depending on device age and availability. Your cost at ZA Support is consistently lower.
+
+Don't let a dead charging port convince you to buy a new device. [Book online at zasupport.com/book](https://zasupport.com/book) for a same-week appointment, or [WhatsApp us on 064 529 5863](https://wa.me/27645295863) to describe your issue first, we'll tell you upfront whether repair or replacement makes sense.
+
+## Frequently Asked Questions
+
+### Q: Can a charging port ever be fixed with software updates?
+
+No. If your device doesn't recognise the charger at all, it's a hardware problem. Software can't create a physical connection that doesn't exist. If your phone *recognises* the charger but charges very slowly, that's sometimes a software setting, try restarting and checking battery health in settings first. But if nothing happens when you plug in, it's hardware, and you need a technician.
+
+### Q: Is it cheaper to repair or replace the entire USB-C board on a Mac?
+
+Repair, every time. A USB-C port replacement on a MacBook is cheaper and faster than replacing the entire logic board. We can usually isolate the port and fix just that component. Full board replacement is reserved for devices where the port damage extends into surrounding circuitry, that's rare, and we'd explain that during your assessment.
+
+### Q: How do I know if my port is corroded or just bent?
+
+You can't without opening it. If you've been using your device in a humid environment (summer in Johannesburg, near pools or kitchens), corrosion is likely. If you've forced a cable in or dropped it, a bent pin is probable. Our R599 diagnostic shows us exactly which it is under our workshop microscope, that information helps us decide repair vs replacement right away.
+
+### Q: Will your warranty cover charging port failure if I drop my phone again?
+
+No. Warranties cover defects in repair, not new damage. If you drop your phone after we repair the port, that's accidental damage, and the warranty doesn't apply to the new damage. However, if the port fails *without* new damage, we repair it free within three years.
+
+### Q: Can I use wireless charging while I wait for a port repair?
+
+Yes, if your device supports it. iPhones 8 and newer have wireless charging. Many newer Android devices do too. Wireless charging is slower than wired, but it works perfectly fine as a temporary solution while your port is being fixed.
+
+### Q: How long does the charging port last after repair?
+
+If the repair is done correctly, the port should last as long as the original, often years. The most common cause of repeat failure is user behaviour: forcing a cable in, exposing the device to moisture, or using cheap third-party chargers that don't fit properly. We provide care instructions at handover, and following those keeps your port healthy long-term.`,
