+    content: `# MacBook Pro 16-Inch Won't Turn On: What We See in Our Hyde Park Workshop and How We Fix It
+
+Your MacBook Pro 16-inch is dead. You've held the power button. Nothing. No chime, no Apple logo, no fan spin, just black glass staring back at you. In our Hyde Park Johannesburg workshop, this is one of the most common calls we field, and the relief in clients' voices when we tell them it's usually fixable is real. We've diagnosed and repaired over 18,000 MacBooks across the Gauteng region, and the "won't turn on" problem lands somewhere in almost every third device that walks through our door.
+
+The good news: a MacBook Pro 16-inch refusing to power on doesn't automatically mean logic-board failure or a R5,000+ repair bill. What it usually means is that one of several predictable components has failed, and we've seen them all.
+
+## Why Your MacBook Pro 16-Inch Stops Powering On
+
+A MacBook Pro 16-inch that won't turn on is almost never a software problem. It's hardware. The machine isn't even getting far enough to load macOS; it's failing at the power-delivery stage, before the system even attempts to boot.
+
+The culprits, in order of likelihood:
+
+**Power adapter failure** is the first thing we check. The 140W USB-C power supply on the 16-inch is robust, but we regularly see them fail, burnt components, frayed cables, or internal short circuits. Clients bring their machine in convinced the logic board is dead, and it's the adapter. We swap in a known-good unit and the Mac fires up immediately.
+
+**Charging port damage** is next. The USB-C port on the 16-inch is soldered to the logic board, and physical stress, yanking the cable, dropping the machine, can fracture solder joints or break the connector itself. The Mac sees no power input and refuses to wake.
+
+**Battery failure** is surprisingly common on older 16-inch models (2019-2021 generation). The battery itself can degrade to a state where it holds almost no charge and the Mac won't power on even when plugged in. The machine requires a minimum voltage from the battery to wake the SMC (System Management Controller), and a dead battery blocks that signal.
+
+**SMC or power-management circuit failure** is rarer but serious. The SMC is the tiny chip that manages power delivery to the logic board. If it fails, your 16-inch becomes completely unresponsive.
+
+We assess your machine with targeted diagnostics: power-adapter testing under load, USB-C continuity checks, battery voltage measurement, and SMC reset attempts. This is why we offer our R599 diagnostic assessment, it isolates the exact failure point and eliminates guesswork.
+
+## Our Hyde Park Repair Process for MacBook Pro 16-Inch Power Issues
+
+When your MacBook Pro 16-inch arrives at our workshop, here's what happens.
+
+First, we test your power adapter on a known-good device. If the adapter charges another Mac without issue, we move forward. If it doesn't, we've found your problem, and the cost is confirmed after assessment.
+
+Next, we perform a hard SMC reset. This clears stuck power-management states that sometimes cause a "dead" MacBook to suddenly wake. We hold the power button, Shift, Control, and Option keys for 10 seconds, release, then power on normally. It works perhaps 8% of the time, but when it does, you're back online for zero parts cost.
+
+If the SMC reset doesn't help, we measure battery voltage with a precision multimeter. A healthy 16-inch battery sits around 15-17 volts. Below 5 volts, and it can't wake the SMC. We'll know immediately whether replacement is required.
+
+Then we move to the USB-C port. We examine the port for visible damage, test continuity on the power pins, and check for burnt or lifted components on the logic board near the charging connector. Port damage is visible under magnification; we spot solder cracks and burnt traces.
+
+If the adapter tests good, the SMC reset fails, the battery is dead, and the port is intact, we suspect a deeper logic-board fault, likely the power-management IC itself. At this stage, we discuss options with you: specialist microsoldering (which we partner with for complex work), or in some cases, whether component-level repair makes financial sense against replacement costs in your situation.
+
+Throughout this process, your machine is covered under our standard assessment-to-repair warranty, and any completed work carries a minimum 1-year guarantee, extendable to 3 years with our premium warranty plan.
+
+## Costs and Turnaround at ZA Support
+
+Our R599 assessment is transparent. Once we've identified the fault, we quote a fixed price for the repair. 
+
+For a failed charging adapter or a straightforward battery replacement, you're looking at confirmed pricing once we assess your unit. USB-C port repair, which involves careful microsoldering and port re-flow, is confirmed after diagnosis. If your logic board has suffered [liquid damage](/liquid-damage), the repair scope widens, and we'll discuss options openly.
+
+Complex [logic-board repairs](/logic-board-repair) involving component-level work are rarer, but when they're needed, we handle them or connect you with our specialist partners. These carry a longer turnaround, typically 5-10 working days, but your machine is safe with us, and we only proceed with your written approval.
+
