+## Why Your M1 MacBook Pro Won't Power On
+
+When an M1 MacBook Pro refuses to turn on, the diagnosis starts with a simple question: is there any sign of life at all?
+
+**No lights, no fans, no response to power button.** This usually means the power delivery chain is broken. The culprit is often a failed charging port, a depleted battery that's stuck in a deep sleep state, or, less commonly, damage to the power management circuitry on the logic board. We've seen load shedding spikes in Johannesburg cause power surges that fry charging-port components. It happens.
+
+**Lights show, but it won't boot.** If the keyboard backlight flickers or the battery indicator LED responds to the MagSafe adapter, but macOS never loads, you're likely looking at a logic-board fault, corrupted firmware, or a failed storage drive. We assess these carefully because the fix varies wildly.
+
+**Kernel panic or restart loop.** The Mac turns on, you see the Apple logo, but then it crashes or restarts before reaching the login screen. This points to RAM failure, SSD corruption, or thermal throttling from a failed cooling system.
+
+Each scenario requires a different approach, which is why our R599 diagnostic assessment is non-negotiable. We connect your M1 to specialist Apple diagnostics tools, test power delivery, check the battery, and inspect the logic board for burn marks or corrosion. Only then do we tell you what's actually broken and what it'll cost to fix.
+
+## Common Causes & How We Repair Them
+
+**Charging Port Failure**
+
+The MagSafe connector on M1 machines is robust, but we've replaced countless ports damaged by physical strain, liquid exposure, or manufacturing defects. If your Mac won't respond to the charger at all, no LED indicator, no power draw, the port is likely the problem.
+
+We remove the bottom case, desolder the old port assembly, and fit a new one. It takes about two hours in our workshop. Cost is confirmed after assessment, but charging-port replacement starts from R1,200.
+
+**Battery Deep Discharge**
+
+If your M1 hasn't been used for months, or if it's been stored in a very cold environment (common during Johannesburg's rare winter snaps), the battery can drop below the threshold needed to wake the power management chip. The Mac won't respond to any button press because the battery is essentially "invisible" to the system.
+
+We connect the device to a specialist trickle charger and leave it for 4-6 hours. Often, the Mac springs back to life. If the battery itself has failed, we replace it. MacBook battery replacement starts from R2,500 and typically takes one working day.
+
+**Logic Board Damage**
+
+This is the scenario nobody wants, but it's not rare. Water damage from spilled coffee, thermal damage from blocked vents, or power surge damage from Johannesburg's unstable grid can knock out power-delivery chips on the logic board itself. We've detailed the repair process in our [logic-board-repair](/logic-board-repair) guide.
+
+If the board is repairable, and many are, we rework the affected components using micro-soldering techniques. If it's beyond recovery, logic-board replacement starts from R3,500. These repairs come with a 3-year warranty on parts and labour.
