+    content: `# MacBook Pro M2 No Power: Diagnosis, Repair, and What You'll Pay in Johannesburg
+
+Your MacBook Pro M2 won't turn on. The screen stays black. You've tried the usual fixes, holding the power button, waiting overnight, plugging in a different charger, and nothing works. The panic sets in: is it the battery? The logic board? Will it cost more than the device is worth?
+
+We've seen this scenario play out hundreds of times in our Hyde Park workshop. The good news: most M2 "no power" issues are fixable, often faster and far cheaper than you'd expect. The bad news: diagnosing the root cause requires proper equipment and hands-on expertise. This guide walks you through what causes M2 power failures, what ZA Support does to fix them, and the genuine costs you'll face here in Johannesburg.
+
+## What Actually Happens When Your M2 Won't Power On
+
+A MacBook that won't power up isn't always a dead battery or a broken screen. The M2 chip has one of the most complex power delivery systems Apple has ever designed. Power flows through multiple stages: the USB-C port connector, the charging control circuit, the SMC (System Management Controller), and finally to the main logic board.
+
+When you bring your M2 to us, we don't assume. We test each stage methodically. We check if the charging port is making proper contact. We measure voltage at key points on the logic board. We run diagnostics to see if the SMC is responding. Over 18,000 MacBooks have passed through our workshop, and the data tells us that roughly 40% of "dead" M2 units are actually fixable without replacing the entire logic board.
+
+The most common culprits we find:
+
+**Charging port corrosion or debris.** Dust, pocket lint, and oxidisation build up inside the USB-C port over months of use. The charger sits loosely. Power doesn't flow. This looks exactly like a battery failure to the untrained eye.
+
+**Battery failure.** The M2 battery is a 52.5Wh lithium-polymer unit. After two to three years of regular charging cycles, or after thermal stress (blocked vents, prolonged heat), the battery can fail completely and won't accept a charge.
+
+**Logic board component failure.** The SMC chip or the power delivery circuitry can fail due to liquid damage, thermal shock, or manufacturing defect. This is rarer but more serious.
+
+**Software/firmware freeze.** Occasionally, an interrupted update or a corrupted SMC firmware state leaves the machine in a state where it won't boot, even though the hardware is fine.
+
+## Our M2 Diagnostic Process at ZA Support Hyde Park
+
+When you walk through our door in Hyde Park with a non-responsive M2, here's what happens.
+
+We start with a **comprehensive R599 assessment**. This is non-negotiable. We don't guess. We connect your M2 to our diagnostic rig, check for power delivery, test the SMC response, and run a series of hardware tests. We inspect the charging port under magnification. We check for signs of liquid damage. This assessment takes 45 minutes and gives us a 95% accurate picture of what's broken.
